	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Caribbean-EU EPA negotiations are launched</h1>

			
			<h4>
												15 September 2004
										</h4>

					</header>


				<div class="intro">

						<p> The Caribbean-EU EPA negotiations were opened in Kingston, Jamaica, on April 15th 2004. In his opening remarks the prime minister of Jamaica, P.J. Patterson, while praising the long-standing partnership with the EU, expressed ‘some disappointment at the lack of a deep transformative effect’ in past arrangements. He emphasised that the Caribbean was approaching the EPA negotiations with a focus on ‘the opportunities that this new arrangement will be able to provide in support of sustainable economic development and poverty alleviation’.</p>

		</div>
		
		
					<p> Emphasis was placed on the need for special and differential treatment, particularly in terms of opening up opportunities for Caribbean services exports. This point was taken up by the Caribbean lead ministerial negotiator, Dame Billie Miller, who stressed the importance of ‘designing an EPA that is appropriate to our small developing economies’. Minister Miller also picked up on the importance of promoting structural change by stressing that EPAs must ‘promote the reduction of vulnerability while facilitating sustainable development’ and enhancing the ‘structural transformation of our economies, international competitiveness and export diversification’.</p><p> The EU Development Commissioner, Poul Nielson, repeated the objectives of the negotiations as set out in the Cotonou Agreement (reduction of poverty, sustainable development, gradual integration into the world economy). Commissioner Nielson did, however, acknowledge that developing countries were already part of the world economy and that what was meant by the expression ‘integration into the world economy’ was ‘creating a better position’ for integration. Commissioner Nielson admitted that in the trade field ‘we need to do more and to do better than in the past’.</p><p> He reiterated the Commission view that ‘EPAs are instruments for development’, maintaining that to date ‘the development dimension has been at the core of the discussion’. Commissioner Nielson then went on to outline some of the main aspects of the development dimension. He reiterated the need to maintain the ‘traditional benefits of trade arrangements both in the North-South context and within your own region’ and the importance of establishing transparent and predictable frameworks for trade, with larger markets which allow economies of scale to be gained and which are more attractive for investment. According to Commissioner Nielson this will ‘contribute to economic growth and poverty reduction’.</p><p> Following on from Commissioner Nielson, Trade Commissioner Pascal Lamy picked up on the need to constantly respond to the dynamic changes in the global economy and highlighted how regional integration formed part of this response. He noted however that progress was not always linear and in this context highlighted how EPAs could help ensure the consolidation of progress in regional market integration by ‘locking in the achievements of those initiatives and enhancing their implementation’. Commissioner Lamy stressed that liberalisation would be asymmetrical with ‘differences in product coverage and the pace and timing of liberalisation’.</p><p> Commissioner Lamy rightly acknowledged that ‘improved market access is not just an issue of tariffs and quotas but also of non-tariff measures’ and the supply capacities of public and private sectors to ‘make the best use of opportunities provided’. In the context of the debate on support for enhancing ACP supply capacities Commissioner Lamy stressed that the EC does not have a mandate to ‘negotiate development finance as part of EPAs’. But he stressed that the EC was ‘committed to making continued progress on this, in parallel with the negotiations, and taking into account the needs arising from the negotiations.’ Commissioner Lamy closed by describing EPAs as a ‘launching pad for effective beneficial integration into the world economy’.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
