		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> In many respects Commissioner Nielson’s speech at the opening of the negotiations is one of the clearest articulations of the limits of the EC’s approach to EPAs to date. He made it clear that EPAs are essentially free-trade areas, with the development dimension being dealt with by policy reforms by the governments concerned, and the redeployment of existing EDF resources towards targeting programmes in areas linked to the EPA process. The Commission, by emphasising the inevitable nature of the policy reforms required, avoids recognising that by requiring ACP countries to go beyond their WTO commitments, the EU will be negotiating agreements which impose additional adjustment costs, at an accelerated rate, on ACP economies entering into EPAs. The failure to recognise this reality enables the EC to avoid its particular responsibility to assist ACP governments in addressing the adjustment costs associated with EPAs. This is especially the case in the agriculture sector. Crucial issues faced in the development of Caribbean-EU trade relations include: how to bring about structural change; at what pace should change be introduced; and how should change be managed through the establishment of flanking measures and support programmes.</p><p> While acknowledging that market access was not just about tariffs and quotas but also non-tariff measures and the development of supply capacities, Commissioner Lamy made no reference to the important issue of the value of trade preferences, an issue of particular importance to the Caribbean with EU rice-sector reform underway and EU sugar-sector reform pending.</p><p> Keeping the issue of additional development finance outside of the formal EPA negotiating framework, will probably mean that the commitments entered into by the EU on financial assistance will be less binding than the provisions of any formal EPA agreement.</p>
		</div>
		
